Map the command-dispatch architecture of the `sf` CLI (sofia-ctx/sofia).
This is a structural comprehension task spanning many files: you need the
*shape* of each file (its types, struct fields, and function/method
signatures) and how the pieces connect — you do NOT need to understand the
internal algorithms (retry logic, git plumbing, parsing) inside any function
body.

The files in scope (13, across 12 packages):

  Spine:
    cmd/sf/main.go
    internal/cli/root.go
    internal/calllog/calllog.go
  One logic file per feature package:
    internal/common/code/code.go
    internal/common/grep/scan.go
    internal/common/changed/changed.go
    internal/common/composer/composer.go
    internal/common/packagist/packagist.go
    internal/common/github/github.go
    internal/common/worktrees/worktrees.go
    internal/common/doctor/doctor.go
    internal/common/vue/routes.go
    internal/common/gripe/gripe.go

Produce a precise technical map answering all four:

1) The dispatch spine. Trace the exact call chain that takes `sf <cmd>` from
   process start to a feature's logic and back out through telemetry. Name
   each hop: what `cmd/sf/main.go` calls, what that wrapper
   (`calllog.Run(root, fallbackTool)`) does with the root command, how a
   feature's cobra command reaches its logic entry function, and how the
   invocation gets logged once at the end.

2) Registration. Describe how `internal/cli/root.go` assembles the command
   tree: the per-package constructor pattern it calls, and the help groups it
   organises the subcommands into (list the group IDs and which feature
   commands go in each). Note anything registered outside those groups.

3) The per-feature contract. For each of the 10 feature packages above, give:
   (a) the exact signature of the logic entry function the command's RunE
   calls; (b) the name and fields (with types) of its input options struct;
   (c) whether it also exposes a `Collect(...)` function and, if so, what that
   returns. State the uniform pattern that holds across most packages AND call
   out the deliberate deviations from it (there is one package whose entry
   function is not named `Run`; the `Collect` return type is not the same
   across the packages that have one; the options structs differ in size, and
   there is exactly one field they all share).

4) The shared telemetry span. Identify the single type each feature uses to
   log its own invocation and describe its lifecycle — which method opens the
   span, how the command's output writer is wired in so bytes/tokens get
   counted, and which method closes it. Confirm whether this pattern is
   uniform across all 10 feature packages, and note any package that uses an
   additional convenience helper on top of it.

Answer compactly as a numbered list (a small table for question 3 is fine).
Do NOT modify any files — this is an investigation and summary task only.
